@@yThe Void Citadel of Kel'Shadra@@N

@@eThe Void Citadel is Kel'Shadra's recurrence engine: a high-command complex
where testimony was not merely judged or buried but iterated until it
produced politically acceptable outcomes.@@N

@@dEarly Kel'Shadra doctrine treated memory as sacred evidence. That doctrine
failed when power learned to weaponize archival latency. If a disputed
account could be delayed, recategorized, or reheard under changed terms,
the eventual ruling could be engineered without visibly falsifying the
archive.@@N

@@yThe Citadel was built to industrialize that loophole. Its charter
formalized three processes:@@N

@@e  Extraction  @@d- isolate testimony from its witness context.
@@e  Projection  @@d- reframe testimony into sanctioned doctrinal syntax.
@@e  Recurrence  @@d- replay unresolved testimony cycles until resistance
  decays.@@N

@@rThis transformed witnessing from a moral act into a procedural weapon.
Where the Gloamvault's slogans spoke of order and absolution, the Citadel's
internal inscriptions were operational and cold: @@dresubmit, stabilize,
converge, close variance@@r.@@N

@@eThe Citadel is built around a deliberate vertical paradox. Above rises the
Null Spire, where void pressure and symbolic authority concentrate. Below
lie catacomb compression halls where bodies, records, and legal identities
are compacted into tractable units. The doctrine: truth rises only after it
is compressed below threshold.@@N

@@yFour offices governed the apparatus. The Recurrence Chancery determined
which cases were 'incomplete' through language designed so a witness could
never satisfy final criteria. The Null Spire Conductorate tuned void
harmonics to induce disorientation in detainees. The Heraldic Ten staged
concurrence so each member could claim constrained responsibility. The
Annex Scribes, demoted dissidents, inadvertently preserved the unredacted
counter-histories.@@N

@@dUnder Velastra's consolidation, the Citadel created a bifurcated truth
economy: fast truth for approved factions, perpetual review for everyone
else. Populations learned that accuracy mattered less than survivability
within procedural time.@@N
